
                        AX-12+ SERVO CONTROL -- Version 1.0
                    Arizona Robotics Research Group (ARRG)

##############################################################################
################         WHAT IS AX-12+ SERVO CONTROL?        ################
##############################################################################
The ROS package "ax12" provides an easy to use interface to the AX-12+ servos
manufactured by Robotis and sold in the Bioloid kits. With this package you
will not have to worry about handling the indivdual bytes and instruction
packets required to control the servos. Simply publish a Move type ROS message
to the ROS topic "robot/ax12/moves" and the ax12 package does the rest. If you
are interested in the data the servo has to offer, simply subscribe to the ROS
topic "robot/ax12/dynamixel1" (where the 1 is the servo's id). Subscribers to
this topic receive MotorData type ROS messages that contain the following
information: servo id and current position, speed, load, voltage, and
temperature.

##############################################################################
################              SYSTEM REQUIREMENTS             ################
##############################################################################

Software Dependencies

-- ROS --
    - This software was designed for use within the Robot Operating System (ROS)
    - Information about ROS as well its installation procedures can be found at
        http://www.ros.org/wiki/

-- pyserial --
    - The installation of the Python module Python Serial Port Extension
        (pyserial) is required for communication with the Robotis AX-12+ servos.
    - Information about pyserial as well its installation procedures can be
        found at http://sourceforge.net/projects/pyserial/

Hardware Dependencies

-- USB2Dynamixel --
    - This software was designed for use with the Robotis AX-12+ servos. The
        software was created to be used with the Robotis USB2Dynamixel Adapter.
        The adapter allows for serial port communication with the servos.
    - Information about the USB2Dynamixel Adapter can be found at
        http://www.trossenrobotics.com/robotis-bioloid-usb2dynamixel.aspx
        
    - The USB2Dynamixel uses an FTDI transceiver chip to interface between the
        servo bus and your computer's USB port.
    - Drivers for the FTDI chip can be downloaded at
        http://www.ftdichip.com/Drivers/VCP.htm

-- SMPS2Dynamixel --
    - When using the Robotis AX-12+ servos, the USB2Dynamixel will not provide
        sufficient power to run the motors.
    - There are two options here:
        1) Use a SMPS2Dynamixel Adapter. (Recommended for starting quickly)
        2) Use the CM-5 that comes with the Bioloid kit (may require some
            changing of its default behaviors so it doesn't begin running its
            own motor control)
    - The SMPS2Dynamixel Adapter uses the standard power brick that comes with
        the Bioloid kit
    - Information about the SMPS2Dynamixel Adapter can be found at
        http://www.trossenrobotics.com/store/p/5886-SMPS2Dynamixel-Adapter.aspx

Platform Specific Dependencies

-- Mac OS X --
    - This software has been tested on an Intel based Mac OS X Version 10.5.8
    - It is highly recommended to use the Python (2.5.1) that comes with OS X
        There were issues communicating with the servos at 1000000 bps when
        using a MacPorts installed Python.
    - Note that on OS X the USB2Dynamixel will show up in devices as something
        like "/dev/tty.usbserial-A9005MZc" where the last part after the hyphen
        is the serial number of your USB2Dynamixel Adapter.

-- Ubuntu --
    - This software has been tested on an Intel based Ubuntu 9.10
    - The USB2Dynamixel shows up in devices as a standard USB device
        "/dev/ttyUSB0" where the last digit will be based upon the order in
        which USB devices are connected.

-- Windows --
    - This software has NOT been tested on any Windows machines.
    - It may be possible to use it since Python is cross-platform.
    - There is no support for any Windows users

